# JSON:API Data Access

All Drupal data fetching lives in `src/lib/drupal.ts` and is called exclusively from
Server Components, Server Actions, or Route Handlers.

## Two fetch helpers — pick the right one

| Helper | When to use |
|---|---|
| `drupalFetch(path, init?)` | Authenticated requests — reads `access_token` httpOnly cookie |
| `drupalPublicFetch(path, init?)` | Public read-only endpoints — no token required |

Both helpers MUST set `Accept: application/vnd.api+json` and prefix with
`process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL`. NEVER construct the base URL inline at the call site.

```ts
// ✅ GOOD – src/lib/drupal.ts
import { cookies } from "next/headers";

const BASE = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL; // http://fashion-simulator.ddev.site

export async function drupalFetch(path: string, init: RequestInit = {}) {
  const token = cookies().get("access_token")?.value;
  return fetch(`${BASE}${path}`, {
    ...init,
    headers: {
      Accept: "application/vnd.api+json",
      ...(token ? { Authorization: `Bearer ${token}` } : {}),
      ...init.headers,
    },
  });
}

export async function drupalPublicFetch(path: string, init: RequestInit = {}) {
  return fetch(`${BASE}${path}`, {
    ...init,
    headers: { Accept: "application/vnd.api+json", ...init.headers },
  });
}
```

## NEVER fetch Drupal directly from a Client Component

NEVER call `fetch`, `drupalFetch`, or `drupalPublicFetch` inside a `"use client"` file.
ALWAYS fetch in a Server Component (or Server Action) and pass plain data down as props.

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD – Server Component fetches, Client Component receives plain props
// app/articles/page.tsx  (no "use client" directive)
import { drupalPublicFetch } from "@/lib/drupal";

export default async function ArticlesPage() {
  const res = await drupalPublicFetch("/jsonapi/node/article?...");
  const { data } = await res.json() as JsonApiList<Article>;
  return <ArticleList articles={data} />;   // ArticleList may be "use client"
}

// ❌ BAD – fetching from a Client Component
"use client";
useEffect(() => {
  fetch(`${process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL}/jsonapi/node/article`).then(...);
}, []);
```

## Use sparse fieldsets — never fetch all fields

ALWAYS request only the fields you render with `fields[resource_type]=field1,field2`.
NEVER omit `fields[...]` and rely on Drupal returning everything.

```ts
// ✅ GOOD – only the fields the component actually uses
const path =
  "/jsonapi/node/article" +
  "?fields[node--article]=title,body,field_tags,field_image" +
  "&fields[taxonomy_term--tags]=name" +
  "&fields[file--file]=uri";

// ❌ BAD – fetches every field on every relationship
const path = "/jsonapi/node/article";
```

## Use `include` to load relationships in one request

ALWAYS use `include=rel1,rel2` to sideload related resources.
NEVER make a second fetch to resolve a relationship UUID manually.

```ts
// ✅ GOOD – one request returns article + its tags + image file
const path =
  "/jsonapi/node/article" +
  "?fields[node--article]=title,body,field_tags,field_image" +
  "&fields[taxonomy_term--tags]=name" +
  "&fields[file--file]=uri" +
  "&include=field_tags,field_image.field_media_image";

// ❌ BAD – two round trips to resolve the tag
const article = await drupalPublicFetch("/jsonapi/node/article/uuid");
const tag = await drupalPublicFetch(`/jsonapi/taxonomy_term/tags/${article.data.relationships.field_tags.data[0].id}`);
```

## Handle the JSON:API response envelope

JSON:API responses always wrap resources in `data`; sideloaded resources are in `included`.
ALWAYS type responses against the envelope. NEVER access `response.title` directly.

```ts
// Minimal envelope types — expand as needed in src/lib/drupal.ts
interface JsonApiResource<T = Record<string, unknown>> {
  id: string;
  type: string;
  attributes: T;
  relationships?: Record<string, { data: { id: string; type: string } | { id: string; type: string }[] }>;
}

interface JsonApiList<T = Record<string, unknown>> {
  data: JsonApiResource<T>[];
  included?: JsonApiResource[];
  links?: { next?: { href: string }; prev?: { href: string } };
}

interface JsonApiSingle<T = Record<string, unknown>> {
  data: JsonApiResource<T>;
  included?: JsonApiResource[];
}

// ✅ GOOD – typed envelope access
const { data, included } = await res.json() as JsonApiList<{ title: string; body: { value: string } }>;
const title = data[0].attributes.title;

// ❌ BAD – treating the response as a flat object
const { title } = await res.json();
```

## Pagination via `links.next`

When iterating all records, follow `links.next.href` rather than incrementing `page[offset]` manually.

```ts
// ✅ GOOD
let url: string | undefined = `${BASE}/jsonapi/node/article?page[limit]=50`;
while (url) {
  const res = await drupalPublicFetch(url.replace(BASE, ""));
  const body = await res.json() as JsonApiList;
  // process body.data ...
  url = body.links?.next?.href;
}
```
